docs.snippet: BUENOS AIRES, Oct. 14. -- A cable dispatch from Valparaiso says that a naval battle occurred yesterday between British and German cruisers off Coquimbo. The names of the ships are unknown, and no details of the fight are given.

docs.snippet: Immediate financial help and trade credit are necessary to meet conditions in South America, says E.C. O'Brien, ex-United States Minister to Uruguay. The establishment of branches of the National City Bank in Buenos Aires and Rio Janeiro will be...
docs.lead_paragraph: Immediate financial help and trade credit are necessary to meet conditions in South America, says E.C. O'Brien, ex-United States Minister to Uruguay. The establishment of branches of the National City Bank in Buenos Aires and Rio Janeiro will be greatly appreciated in the Republics of Argentine and Brazil, but these branches cannot produce immediate results and afford relief to the general credit difficulty throughout the South American States, he asserts.

headline.main: WANTS CREDIT HERE FOR SOUTH AMERICA; Ex-Minister O'Brien Says This Is the Time for Us to Show a Desire to Help. A GREAT CHANCE FOR TRADE Conference of Bankers Should Be Called, He Thinks, to Establish a System for Commercial Exchange.

docs.snippet: There is no little alarm expressed at the present time by woolen manufacturers at the results which must follow the wool embargoes proclaimed by England, if they prove of considerable duration. The impression is just beginning to grow that the...
docs.lead_paragraph: There is no little alarm expressed at the present time by woolen manufacturers at the results which must follow the wool embargoes proclaimed by England, if they prove of considerable duration. The impression is just beginning to grow that the British Government, in forbidding the export of wool, has gone after two birds with the same stone.

headline.main: ALARM EXPRESSED AT LACK OF WOOL; A Mill Owner's Views on Results of the British Embargo on the Article.

docs.lead_paragraph: THE course of the present Administration in foreign affairs has now and then combined officiously offensive action toward foreign powers with tame submission to wrongdoing by foreign powers. As a nation we have refused to do our duty to others and yet we have at times tamely submitted to wrong at the hands of others.
